I look forward to connecting with you and running plays for you to be successful in the near future.

Off-Shore Wind Turbine Project
	For this project, we planned to design an off-shore floating wind turbine. The main challenge of this project is maintaining the turbine and making sure its stable on the water because the weight distribution of wind turbines is not exactly ideal for a moving base material like water. Another challenge that adds to this is the weather. The turbine has to be able to withstand storms like hurricanes or tsunamis, large waves, possibly even water vehicles or animals that could interfere with its functionality, not to mention much higher wind speeds than land, which is the reason for off-shore turbines in the first place. The wind turbine we constructed must be able to withstand different categories of hurricanes.

projects.description: Murphy Oil Corporation is a holding company that operates two business activities: exploration and production, which explores for and produces crude oil, natural gas and natural gas liquids worldwide; and refining and marketing, which primarily consists of the sale of motor fuel and merchandise. The first section of this report talks about Arkansas’ economy.  In summary, it touches on the population, the employment rates, the largest industries, the state income, and the personal income within the state of Arkansas.  The second section of this report talks about the oil and gas extraction industry in Arkansas.  Specifically, about the number of people employed in this industry, the number of oil and gas extraction companies, the net income of the industry, and the most common product.  The third section of this report discusses in more detail about the location, the mission statement, the number of employees, and the products of Murphy Oil Corporation. Additionally, the financial reports for Murphy Oil Corporation in 2013 are attached in the Appendix. The fourth section of this report provides a description of our renewable energy cost reduction project as well as a breakeven analysis for the projected project.  In our analysis, we estimated what the cost of the project will be and estimated what level of production will be required in order to justify the cost of the project.  Finally, the fifth section of this report wraps up the research paper with a conclusion and summary of each section.
projects.title: Murphy Oil Project

projects.description: In the simulation created in Excel represents a car suspension osculating down a road that is not straight and helps keep the car from bottoming out. The Suspension system need to be able to keep the riders from feeling every bump or change in curvature in the road. The amplitude and the omega was calculated for a period of time to see if the suspension was properly managing the change in the road. During the process the values of C, W(omega), K factor was changed to see how the suspension would respond over a period of time. The amplitude charts listed below show the frequency of the roads and how much the car is bouncing. In a perfect world, you would want little to none amplitude differences in the road. As stated before you also don’t want the car to bottom outThe better the suspension system is in the car the more comfortable the rider will feel. The weight of the vehicle plays a major part in the suspension and the way the vehicle responds to the road. The heavier the vehicle is the more difficult it is to maintain stabilization in the car. On the other hand, the less weight the vehicle has the easier it is for the suspension system to make a smooth ride over a bumpy road. The Suspension system should be able to minimize the amplitude as time goes on. The graph listed below are examples of combinations that minimized the amplitude differences. The wave patterns should go from big to small as the car drives down the road. In general the whole entire main focus of this topic is to find the best combination C, W, and K to minimize the roughness of the road that is created when driving.
projects.title: Dynamics (Spring Mass System demonstrated on Excel)

projects.description:
The main focus of our project is to create a highly effective lockout buzzer system for the Countdown Round of MATHCOUNTS competition. This system needs to meet the clients requirements as stated on the next slide. This system should be competition ready and thoroughly tested. There should be two buzzers with equal response time for two competitors.

Buzzer Requirements
A 45 second timer shall be implemented by the controller (The operator of the manual reset button) if one of the students gets the preceding question wrong. This is so that the other student has 45 seconds in which to buzz in.
The buzzer should withstand the force of a competitor’s impact (minimum 29 lbf).
Must include an indicator, which shows which competitor has hit the buzzer first and lets the audience know as well.
The buzzer must last 10 years.
The controller must be able to reset the buzzer by hand.
There should not be any maintenance and if there is any it should minimal and simple to repair.
​The entire system shall cost a maximum of 250 dollars.
The logo for MATHCOUNTS, ACU​ and NSPE must be included on the buzzers.
projects.title: MATHCounts Lockout Buzzer

projects.description:
DLT Inc. was contracted by Alex Wann to create a latrine design that could be used in Gualaco Honduras, where 30 of the 33 families living there practice open defecation. The latrines were to be designed using local, cheap materials, while meeting a certain set of requirements that were confirmed by the client. The latrines needed to withstand the tropical climate of Honduras, be able to serve a family of around six to eight people for 10-14 years, and decrease the spread of disease via flies, while not having an unpleasant odor. DLT has worked to research various latrine designs, looking to present a design that would be efficient and ideal in Gualaco. 
DLT presented three designs for review, which gave the client several options to decide which design was the best fit for the area and the needs there. The three initial designs for the 50% design review were the single-pit sealed latrine, urine-diverting latrine, and the two-pit pour-flush latrine. To reach a conclusion on which design would be the most ideal, a comparison of various factors such as cost, durability, and compatibility with the requirements was conducted among the three latrines. DLT’s recommendation was the two-pit pour-flush latrine, which the client agreed was the best option. Some aspects of the design were altered by the client during the 50% design report, which gave DLT the necessary information to work towards the final design for the two-pit pour-flush latrine.
projects.title: JR Clinic Latrine System

Exciting a week at the builder show! If you have never been it is definitely worth it. Thank you IBS once again on an amazing week in Vegas. Learned so much more around the building industry. 

#NAHB #IBS #BuilderShow

I am beyond grateful to have been selected and to have participated in the 2024 NAHB International Builders' Show® (IBS) Scholarship Program. This experience was not just an award; it was a profound journey into the heart of the building and construction industry, filled with learning, networking, and discovery.

The IBS Scholarship, a prestigious initiative by the NAHB for members aged 21-35, provided me with an unparalleled opportunity to immerse myself in everything the industry offers. From innovative products to the latest trends, the insights gained have been invaluable.

Highlights of my experience:
📚 Access to the Expo+Education Pass at IBS 2024, where I dove deep into educational sessions and absorbed the latest industry insights.
✈️ The journey itself, supported by roundtrip economy airfare and hotel accommodations, made comfortable and enriching by the thoughtful arrangements.
🤝 Networking and learning opportunities with leading industry experts and peers that have broadened my perspectives and professional network.
🔍 Exposure to new trends and innovative products that are shaping our industry's future, inspiring me to bring fresh ideas back to my work and community.

This experience has been transformative, offering new experiences, professional development, and connections that will undoubtedly influence my career path and contributions to the building and construction industry.
A heartfelt thank you to the NAHB and the IBS Scholarship Committee for this incredible opportunity. The knowledge and connections I've gained are treasures I will carry forward in my career.

As I reflect on this journey, I am more excited than ever about the future of our industry and my role within it. Here's to continuous learning, innovation, and building a brighter future together!
